the right practice on the right day always happens. the poses were challenging and invigorating to get my mind on my body and what i CAN help to control, my breath and my movement...and i was struggling struggling struggling to feel or find the light when my memories keep tracking back to where I was 20 years ago in Colorado schools...or where I was this morning when saying goodbye to my Colorado school student (daughter in 2nd grade.)...and then there you were, to tell me, we honor the darkness too. my hands touched my heart and I was there in the practice again. Finding what felt good.

My second time through Dedicate.  In the midst of this "Light" practice, what suddenly surfaced was an awareness of my fear of "my light."  It was crystal clear:  that I knew who I was in my deepest being; it was time to let go of the fear of allowing that "me" to be fully visible -- to lead my external life.  That awareness also illuminated how I had allowed myself to stay trapped or confined in situations that fueled that fear. . . . 

; 
Trusting the process (not only of yoga but of the fullness of our faith) that when we are ready to "see," it will be revealed.  I have dedicated both of my "Dedicate" journeys to "openness to true love."  Not seeking "someone" but rather to be able to live more deeply into the last lines of a song that came to me once about my life:  "When my body returns to the earth, my breath returns to the wind;  I will have offered what is mine to offer; I will have loved with all I am."

Yesterday when I practice "light" for the first time i didn't connect to it at all. It was one of those days where I am just waiting for instructions, I'm not in the moment nor do I feel an inspiration to make the practice more "my own". So I decided to try it again today and... It worked! It was a very satisfying practice, notwithstanding the fact that my inner thighs muscles are the tightest of a pretty tight body. But still, I made changes where I felt I wanted or needed them, and overall the journey was really nice. This makes me realize that we are really "the captains of our fates, the masters of our souls". Our attitude makes a huge difference. And I don't say that as a way of "shaming" someone. Days when you don't feel it are normal. Embrace your humanity, and just know that you have the possibility and the ability to be a light... Tomorrow or in ten days or one year, it doesn't matter how long it takes, you have this superpower. 
Thank you Adriene for the amazing experience you're providing.

I'm a high school teacher and today I asked my students how they were doing on their new year's goals. I told them I've done yoga every day this month, and an athlete asked "what's the point of yoga? What does yoga even do?" At first I was shocked that this could even be a question, then I was flooded with emotions and memories from all the practices I've done. I said it helps with your flexibility and stamina, but it also helps with physical, emotional and spiritual health. He was shocked and said, oh, there's a spiritual level to it? And I was like absolutely, for me there is! I wish I could teach my students about yoga every day :D

My question for myself today:  How can I shine my light so brightly with the world (regardless of how my body temple is feeling).  Yoga teaches me that is not about waiting for the someday in the future.  I show up NOW with whatever is appearing over and over and over.
